{
  "texts": [
    "For each of these minimal cells, pollsters would be required to provide an estimate of the 'weight' associated with each cell (i.e., an estimate of how many people of 'this kind' exist amongst voters, according to their models), as well as a probability to vote for a given party.",
    "The polling association could then, during or at the end of the election, produce a set of 'benchmark' predictions and weights based on an optimal sample and model.",
    "A comparison between the pollsters' estimates and the benchmarks could then inform the public on whether the predictions were endowed with specific biases-e.g., a given pollster may have produced predictions for cells involving women indicating they were on average 30% more likely to vote for the Conservatives than the benchmark provided by the polling association.",
    "Note here that some pollsters may wish to withhold a complete set of weights and predictions for commercial reasons.",
    "The level of specificity of these 'minimal' cells would not be so deep as to jeopardise the commercial interest of any pollster."
  ]
}